rds|1978]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| ''[[Autumn Sonata]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=THE 51ST ACADEMY AWARDS 1979|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1979|publisher=Oscars|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Primetime Emmy Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| [[12th Primetime Emmy Awards|1960]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Actress in a Limited Series or TV Movie]]\n|''The Turn of the Screw''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=12th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1960|publisher=Emmys|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[13th Primetime Emmy Awards|1961]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Actress in a Limited Series or TV Movie]]\n| ''24 Hours in a Woman's Life''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=13th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1961|publisher=Emmys|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[34th Primetime Emmy Awards|1982]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Actress in a Limited Series or TV Movie]]\n| ''[[A Woman Called Golda]]''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=34th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1982|publisher=Emmys|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Tony Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| [[1st Tony Awards|1947]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Leading Actress in a Play]]\n| ''[[Joan of Lorraine]]''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=About Ingrid|url=http://www.ingridbergman.com/about/bio2.htm|publisher=Ingrid Bergman.com|accessdate=20 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811082912/http://www.ingridbergman.com/about/bio2.htm|archivedate=11 August 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n[[Woody Guthrie]] composed \"Ingrid Bergman\", a song about Bergman in 1950. The lyrics have been described as \"erotic\" and makes reference to Bergman's relationship with [[Roberto Rossellini]], which began during work on the film ''[[Stromboli (film)|Stromboli]]''. This song was never recorded by Guthrie but it was set to music and recorded by [[Billy Bragg]] on the album ''[[Mermaid Avenue]]'' after being discovered in the Woody Guthrie Archive with thousands of other songs.<ref>{{cite interview|url=http://www.songfacts.com/blog/interviews/anna_canoni_about_woody_guthrie/|title=Anna Canoni about Woody Guthrie|first=Anna|last=Canoni|others=Carl Wiser|work=Song facts}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book|author1=Bergman, Ingrid|author2=Burgess, Alan|authorlink2=Alan Burgess|title=Ingrid Bergman: My Story|url=https://archive.org/details/ingridbergmanmys00berg|url-access=registration|publisher=Delacorte Press|year=1980|location=New York|isbn=0-440-03299-7}}\n* {{cite book|author=Chandler, Charlotte|authorlink=Charlotte Chandler|title=Ingrid: Ingrid Bergman, A Personal Biography|publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=2007|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7432-9421-8|url=https://archive.org/details/ingridingridberg00chan}}\n* {{cite book|author=Leamer, Laurence|authorlink=Laurence Leamer|title=As Time Goes By: The Life of Ingrid Bergman|publisher=Harper & Row|year=1986|location=New York|isbn=0-06-015485-3|url=https://archive.org/details/astimegoesbylif00leam}}\n* {{cite book|author=Dagrada, Elena|title=Le Varianti Trasparenti. I Film con Ingrid Bergman di Roberto Rossellini|publisher=LED Edizioni Universitarie|year=2008|location=Milano|isbn=978-88-7916-410-8}}\n