{"title_page": "John Doe (whistleblower)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|John Doe (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}'''[[John Doe]]''' is the [[pseudonym]] used by the [[whistleblower]] in the 2016 [[Panama Papers]] leak, who turned over 11.5 million documents from the law firm [[Mossack Fonseca]] to the newspaper ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]''.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|last1=Levy\n|first1=Megan\n|title='Interested in data?': Panama Papers leak began with message from 'John Doe'\n|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/banking-and-finance/interested-in-data-panama-papers-leak-began-with-message-from-john-doe-20160405-gnzd0i.html\n|accessdate=April 6, 2016\n|work=Sydney Morning Herald\n|date=April 6, 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|author1=International Consortium of Investigative Journalists\n|author2=Elise Worthington\n|title=Panama Papers: Why 'John Doe' risked their life for the Mossack Fonseca leak\n|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-05/why-the-panama-papers-mossack-fonseca-leaks-really-matters/7300262\n|accessdate=April 6, 2016\n|work=ABC News\n|date=April 5, 2016\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n|last1=Hines\n|first1=Nicho\n|title=Panama Papers Leaker: 'I Want to Make These Crimes Public'\n|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/04/panama-papers-leaker-i-want-to-make-these-crimes-public.html\n|accessdate=April 6, 2016\n|work=The Daily Beast\n|date=April 4, 2016\n}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, Doe published a statement titled ''The Revolution Will Be Digitized''<ref>{{cite web|title=Panama Papers Source Offers Documents To Governments, Hints At More To Come|url=https://www.icij.org/investigations/panama-papers/20160506-john-doe-statement/|accessdate=Jan 12, 2020}}</ref>; Doe explained he made the files public to underline growing [[income inequality]] and financial corruption globally. The whistleblower has offered to help prosecutors build their cases, on condition of legal protection.<ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Panama Papers Source Offers to Aid Inquiries if Exempt From Punishment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/07/world/panama-papers-source.html|accessdate=May 8, 2016|work=NYT|date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Initial contact with ''S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung''==\nIn 2014, Doe contacted [[Bastian Obermayer]], a reporter working for German newspaper ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]],'' with the message \"Hello. This is John Doe. Interested in data?\" When Obermayer answered in the affirmative, Doe continued, saying, \"There are a couple of conditions. My life is in danger. We will only chat over encrypted files. No meeting, ever.\" When Obermayer asked Doe why he was leaking the data, Doe responded that he sought to \"make these crimes public.\" He then proceeded to transfer roughly 11.5 million documents from the records of Panamanian law firm [[Mossack Fonseca]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farhi|first1=Paul|title=\u2018Hello. This is John Doe\u2019: The mysterious message that launched the Panama Papers|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/hello-this-is-john-doe-the-mysterious-message-that-launched-the-panama-papers/2016/04/06/59305838-fc0c-11e5-886f-a037dba38301_story.html|accessdate=April 7, 2016|work=Daily Mail|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> When the data was eventually released to the public, it became known as the Panama Papers.\n\n== ''The Revolution Will Be Digitized'' ==\nDoe issued a statement through ''S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung'' on May 5, 2016, explaining what motivated him to release the massive trove of files.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Franco|first1=Arnulfo|title=John Doe, mysterious whistleblower behind Panama Papers, finally speaks|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/article76059762.html|accessdate=May 7, 2016|work=The Miami Herald|agency=Associated Press|date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn this text, titled ''The Revolution Will Be Digitized'', Doe said growing global income inequality and corruption allegedly enabled by Mossack Fonseca motivated his actions. Doe also said the papers demonstrated the injustices perpetrated by the industry that creates offshore companies and blamed governments for allowing offshore havens to proliferate, saying he leaked the documents \"simply because I understood enough about their contents to realise the scale of the injustices they described.\" He added that he had never worked for any government or intelligence agency and expressed willingness to help prosecutors. After ''S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung'' verified that it was from the Panama Papers source, the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] (ICIJ) posted the full written statement on its website.<ref>{{cite web|title=Panama Papers: Source breaks silence on Mossack Fonseca leaks |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-36232142|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://panamapapers.icij.org/20160506-john-doe-statement.html#_ga=1.164154486.836406132.1459807380 |title=Panama Papers Source Offers Documents To Governments, Hints At More To Come |date= May 6, 2016 |accessdate=May 8, 2016 |publisher=ICIJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Panama Papers leak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doe, John}}\n[[Category:Unidentified people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Panama Papers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Men whistleblowers]]\n\n\n{{Criminal-law-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|John Doe (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}'''[[John Doe]]''' is the [[pseudonym]] used by the [[whistleblower]] in the 2016 [[Panama Papers]] leak, who turned over 11.5 million documents from the law firm [[Mossack Fonseca]] to the newspaper ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]''.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|last1=Levy\n|first1=Megan\n|title='Interested in data?': Panama Papers leak began with message from 'John Doe'\n|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/banking-and-finance/interested-in-data-panama-papers-leak-began-with-message-from-john-doe-20160405-gnzd0i.html\n|accessdate=April 6, 2016\n|work=Sydney Morning Herald\n|date=April 6, 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|author1=International Consortium of Investigative Journalists\n|author2=Elise Worthington\n|title=Panama Papers: Why 'John Doe' risked their life for the Mossack Fonseca leak\n|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-05/why-the-panama-papers-mossack-fonseca-leaks-really-matters/7300262\n|accessdate=April 6, 2016\n|work=ABC News\n|date=April 5, 2016\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n|last1=Hines\n|first1=Nicho\n|title=Panama Papers Leaker: 'I Want to Make These Crimes Public'\n|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/04/panama-papers-leaker-i-want-to-make-these-crimes-public.html\n|accessdate=April 6, 2016\n|work=The Daily Beast\n|date=April 4, 2016\n}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, Doe published a statement titled ''The Revolution Will Be Digitized''<ref>{{cite web|title=Panama Papers Source Offers Documents To Governments, Hints At More To Come|url=https://www.icij.org/investigations/panama-papers/20160506-john-doe-statement/|accessdate=Jan 12, 2020}}</ref>; Doe explained he made the files public to underline growing [[income inequality]] and financial corruption globally. The whistleblower has offered to help prosecutors build their cases, on condition of legal protection.<ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Panama Papers Source Offers to Aid Inquiries if Exempt From Punishment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/07/world/panama-papers-source.html|accessdate=May 8, 2016|work=NYT|date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Initial contact with ''S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung''==\nIn 2014, Doe contacted [[Bastian Obermayer]], a reporter working for German newspaper ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]],'' with the message \"Hello. This is John Doe. Interested in data?\" When Obermayer answered in the affirmative, Doe continued, saying, \"There are a couple of conditions. My life is in danger. We will only chat over encrypted files. No meeting, ever.\" When Obermayer asked Doe why he was leaking the data, Doe responded that he sought to \"make these crimes public.\" He then proceeded to transfer roughly 11.5 million documents from the records of Panamanian law firm [[Mossack Fonseca]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farhi|first1=Paul|title=\u2018Hello. This is John Doe\u2019: The mysterious message that launched the Panama Papers|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/hello-this-is-john-doe-the-mysterious-message-that-launched-the-panama-papers/2016/04/06/59305838-fc0c-11e5-886f-a037dba38301_story.html|accessdate=April 7, 2016|work=Daily Mail|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> When the data was eventually released to the public, it became known as the Panama Papers.\n\n== ''The Revolution Will Be Digitized'' ==\nDoe issued a statement through ''S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung'' on May 5, 2016 explaining what motivated him to release the massive trove of files.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Franco|first1=Arnulfo|title=John Doe, mysterious whistleblower behind Panama Papers, finally speaks|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/article76059762.html|accessdate=May 7, 2016|work=The Miami Herald|agency=Associated Press|date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn this text, titled ''The Revolution Will Be Digitized'', Doe said growing global income inequality and corruption allegedly enabled by Mossack Fonseca motivated his actions. Doe also said the papers demonstrated the injustices perpetrated by the industry that creates offshore companies and blamed governments for allowing offshore havens to proliferate, saying he leaked the documents \"simply because I understood enough about their contents to realise the scale of the injustices they described.\" He added that he had never worked for any government or intelligence agency and expressed willingness to help prosecutors. After ''S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung'' verified that it was from the Panama Papers source, the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] (ICIJ) posted the full written statement on its website.<ref>{{cite web|title=Panama Papers: Source breaks silence on Mossack Fonseca leaks |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-36232142|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://panamapapers.icij.org/20160506-john-doe-statement.html#_ga=1.164154486.836406132.1459807380 |title=Panama Papers Source Offers Documents To Governments, Hints At More To Come |date= May 6, 2016 |accessdate=May 8, 2016 |publisher=ICIJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Panama Papers leak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doe, John}}\n[[Category:Unidentified people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Panama Papers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Men whistleblowers]]\n\n\n{{Criminal-law-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Longdonwong", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Revolution Will Be Digitized", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Doe_(whistleblower)"}
{"title_page": "Death Before Dishonor (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Death Before Dishonor\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[2 Pistols]]\n| cover      = 2PistolsDeathBeforeDishonor.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 17, 2008\n| recorded   = 2007-2008\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 54:54\n| label      = Blood Money Union/[[Universal Republic]]\n| producer   = [[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]], [[Honorable C.N.O.T.E.]], Coni' Cone, Bolo \"Da\" Producer, [[D. A. Doman|D.A. on the Track Man]], Yung Chill\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Death Before Dishonor\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[She Got It]]\n | single1date = January 8, 2008<ref>http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239#2008</ref>\n | single2     = [[You Know Me (2 Pistols song)|You Know Me]]\n | single2date = May 27, 2008\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Death Before Dishonor''''' is the debut album by rapper [[2 Pistols]], released on June 17, 2008. Guests include [[T-Pain]], [[Tay Dizm]], [[Ray J]], [[Slick Pulla]], [[Blood Raw]], [[Trey Songz]], BMU & [[Tyra Bolling|Tyra B]]. A version of \"Candy Coated Diamonds\" featuring [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]] (instead of Tyra B) leaked on various [[The Black Eyed Peas]] fansites.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000788640|pure_url=yes}}|title=Death Before Dishonor - 2 Pistols|last=Jeffries|first=David|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref>\n|rev2 = DJBooth\n|rev2score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"DJB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/2-pistols-death-before-dishonor-0617081/|title=2 Pistols - Death Before Dishonor|last=Slavik|first=Nathan|website=DJBooth|date=June 17, 2008|accessdate=August 4, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219175850/http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/2-pistols-death-before-dishonor-0617081/|archivedate=February 19, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''RapReviews''\n|rev3score = 4/10<ref name=\"RR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2008_07_deathbeforedishonor.html|title=2 Pistols :: Death Before Dishonor :: Universal Republic Records|last=Hernandez|first=Pedro|website=RapReviews|date=July 8, 2008|accessdate=December 4, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n''Death Before Dishonor'' received mixed reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. [[AllMusic]] editor David Jeffries was mixed towards the album, praising the J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League's production but felt there were less quality street tracks to give it enough quality, concluding with, \"Way too little, way too late to call this a compelling debut, but just like any given [[Rick Ross|Ross]] album, ''Death Before Dishonor'' has singles to spare and enough of that Florida flavor to keep fans happy.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> DJBooth's Nathan Slavik also gave praise to the production but found 2 Pistols to be an average rapper that delivers sub-standard street tracks, saying that \"''Death Before Dishonor'' doesn\u2019t exactly cover a lot of musical ground, it\u2019s essentially 'She Got It' and 'Eyes Closed' remixed and re-titled for an entire album.\"<ref name=\"DJB\"/> Pedro Hernandez of ''RapReviews'' criticized the album for having nondescript party tracks with faceless production and 2 Pistols for only having the basics of hip-hop content, concluding that \"If you absolutely love this type of rap and already ran through the good stuff, 2 Pistols might be something to hold you over. For all others, ''Death Before Dishonor'' is about as enjoyable as having '2 Pistols' and no ammo.\"<ref name=\"RR\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Title\n! Producer\n! Featured guest(s)\n! Time\n|-\n|1\n|\"Intro\"\n|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]\n|\n|0:59\n|-\n|2\n|\"Death Before Dishonor\"\n|Da Honorable C.N.