{"title_page": "Hieu Van Le", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image               = Hieu Van Le 2015.jpg\n| honorific-prefix    = [[Excellency|His Excellency]] [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Hieu Van Le\n| honorific-suffix    = {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AC}}\n| order               = 35th\n| office              = Governor of South Australia\n| term_start          = 1 September 2014\n| term_end            = \n| lieutenant_governor = [[Brenda Wilson]]\n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| premier             = [[Jay Weatherill]]<br>[[Steven Marshall]]\n| predecessor         = [[Kevin Scarce]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = Lieutenant Governor of South Australia \n| term_start1         = 31 August 2007\n| term_end1           = 15 August 2014\n| governor1           = Kevin Scarce\n| predecessor1        = Bruno Krumins\n| successor1          = Brenda Wilson\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1954|1|1}}\n| birth_place         = [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb (town)|Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb]], [[State of Vietnam]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = \n| spouse              = Lan T. Phuong Le\n| relations           = \n| children            = Kim Anh Le<br/>Don Anh Le\n| residence           = [[Government House, Adelaide|Government House]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Dalat University]]<br/>[[University of Adelaide]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = Accountant<br>Economist\n| religion            = Catholic<ref name=\"TSC\" />\n| signature           = \n| website             = [http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/ Governor.sa.gov.au]\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Hieu Van Le''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AC}} ({{lang-vi|L\u00ea V\u0103n Hi\u1ebfu}}; born 1 January 1954) is the 35th and current [[Governor of South Australia]], in office since 1 September 2014. He served as the state's [[Lieutenant-Governor (Australia)|lieutenant-governor]] from 2007 to 2014. He also served as chair of the South Australian Multicultural and Ethnic Affairs Commission (SAMEAC) from 2006 to 2009. Le is the first person [[Asian Australian|of Asian heritage]] to be appointed a state governor in Australia.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/state-politics/sa-governor-hieu-van-le-a-beacon-of-hope/story-e6frgczx-1227044320635?nk=a992bb8f1bd9a4eac9e7ae1c3765fd17| title=SA Governor Hieu Van Le 'a beacon of hope'| last=Martin| first=Sarah| newspaper=The Australian| date=2 September 2014| accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLe was born in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb]], [[South Vietnam]], on 1 January 1954. He was raised and educated in [[\u0110\u00e0 N\u1eb5ng]], and attended [[Dalat University]]. He fled Vietnam from the new communist regime in November 1977, and came by boat to [[Darwin, Northern Territory]], as a refugee in 1977 with his wife Lan and about 40 other people.<ref name=\"ADV26June\">{{cite news |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/south-australia-premier-jay-weatherill-names-hieu-van-le-as-next-governor/story-fni6uo1m-1226967500337?nk=5d3db46284fe3814b9f78235c2ef1550 |title=South Australia Premier Jay Weatherill names Hieu Van Le as next Governor |publisher=News Limited |work=The Advertiser |last=Holderhead |first=Sheradyn |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> Their two sons were born in Australia and are named after Australian cricketers [[Donald Bradman|Sir Donald Bradman]] and [[Kim Hughes]].<ref name=\"ABCNewsAppt\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-06-26/hieu-van-le-appointed-sa-governor/5552004 |title=Hieu Van Le to be next SA Governor: From war-torn Vietnam to vice-regal post |date=26 June 2014|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter arriving in Australia, Le attended the [[University of Adelaide]], receiving a [[Master of Business Administration]] and an Economics degree. He was a senior investigator and manager with the [[Australian Securities and Investments Commission]] from the early 1990s until his retirement in 2009.<ref name=\"PressJune2014\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.premier.sa.gov.au/images/news_releases/14_06June/governor.pdf |title=Hieu Van Le to be appointed as South Australia's next Governor |publisher=[[Government of South Australia]] |agency=Premier of South Australia |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924081200/http://www.premier.sa.gov.au/images/news_releases/14_06June/governor.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is also a member of the [[Australian Society of Certified Practising Accountants]] (CPA) and a Fellow Member of the [[Financial Services Institute of Australasia]] (Finsia).\n\n==Governor==\nLe's appointment as [[Governor of South Australia]] to replace [[Kevin Scarce]] was announced on 26 June 2014; he took office on 1 September, with Scarce's term expiring on 7 August.<ref name=\"ABCNewsAppt\" /><ref>{{cite web| date=13 February 2012| url=http://www.news.com.au/national/rear-admiral-kevin-scarce-to-stay-on-as-south-australia-governor/story-e6frfkp9-1226269990532| title=Rear Admiral Kevin Scarce to stay on as South Australia governor| publisher=news.com.au. |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> Le is a Catholic and credits his experiences as a refugee for strengthening his religious convictions.<ref name=\"TSC\">{{cite news | url=http://www.caa.wt2.com.au/sites/SouthernCross/features?more=5356 | title=Life's no accident | work=[[The Southern Cross (South Australia)|The Southern Cross]] | accessdate=18 December 2014 | author=DiGirolamo, Rebecca | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218001023/http://www.caa.wt2.com.au/sites/SouthernCross/features?more=5356 | archive-date=18 December 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In June 2019, Premier [[Steven Marshall]] announced that Le's original term as governor had been extended by two years, to 31 August 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://7news.com.au/politics/south-australian-governor-hieu-van-le-has-his-term-extended-by-two-years-c-157471|title=South Australian Governor Hieu Van Le has his term extended by two years|publisher=7 News|date=10 June 2019|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles and honours==\n{{Infobox viceroy styles\n| image = [[File:Badge of the Governor of South Australia.svg|50px]]\n| name = Hieu Van Le<br />(2018\u2013present)\n| dipstyle = His Excellency the Honourable\n| offstyle = Your Excellency\n| altstyle = Sir\n}}\n\n===Honours===\n;Orders\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2010: [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] (AO)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1141697&search_type=quick&showInd=true |title=LE, Hieu Van |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=It's An Honour |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2014: [[Knight of Grace of the Order of St John]]\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2016: [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC)<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-06-13/sa-governor-hieu-van-le-recognised-with-a-qc/7502538 Queen's Birthday honours: SA Governor Hieu Van Le recognised with Companion Order] ''ABC News'', 13 June 2016. Retrieved 13 June 2016.</ref>\n\n;Medals\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2001: [[Centenary Medal]] \"for service to the advancement of multiculturalism in Australia\",<ref name=\"PressJune2014\"/>\n\n;Appointments\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2014: Colonel of the [[Royal South Australia Regiment]].\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} 2014: [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Deputy Prior of the Order of St John]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding the Most Venerable Order of St John|url=https://www.stjohnsa.com.au/cms_resources/Understanding%20the%20Most%20Venerable%20Order%20of%20St%20John.pdf|website=Governor of New South Wales|publisher=Governor of New South Wales|accessdate=24 August 2018|date=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Le Van Hieu}}\n* [http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/node/27 His Excellency the Honourable Hieu Van Le AO] at Government House SA\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080721004219/http://multicultural.sa.gov.au/commission/hieu_van_le.htm Bio Hieu Van Le] at the South Australian Multicultural and Ethnic Affairs Commission (SAMEAC)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080730034747/http://www.ministers.sa.gov.au/news.php?id=2090 From refugee to Lieutenant Governor]\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/sa/content/2006/s1935506.htm ''Stateline'' Interview] at [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bruno Krumins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lieutenant-Governor of South Australia]]|years=2007\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brenda Wilson]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kevin Scarce]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of South Australia]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian governors}}\n{{Governors of South Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Le, Hieu Van}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian accountants]]\n[[Category:Australian economists]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant-Governors of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Governors of South Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Centenary Medal]]\n[[Category:University of Adelaide alumni]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese refugees]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n\n\n{{australia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image               = Hieu Van Le 2015.jpg\n| honorific-prefix    = [[Excellency|His Excellency]] [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Hieu Van Le\n| honorific-suffix    = {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AC}}\n| order               = 35th\n| office              = Governor of South Australia\n| term_start          = 1 September 2014\n| term_end            = \n| lieutenant_governor = [[Brenda Wilson]]\n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| premier             = [[Jay Weatherill]]<br>[[Steven Marshall]]\n| predecessor         = [[Kevin Scarce]]\n| successor           = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1954|1|1}}\n| birth_place         = [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb (town)|Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb]], [[State of Vietnam]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = \n| spouse              = Lan T. Phuong Le\n| relations           = \n| children            = Kim Anh Le<br/>Don Anh Le\n| residence           = [[Government House, Adelaide|Government House]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Dalat University]]<br/>[[University of Adelaide]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = Accountant<br>Economist\n| religion            = Catholic<ref name=\"TSC\" />\n| signature           = \n| website             = [http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/ Governor.sa.gov.au]\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Hieu Van Le''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AC}} ({{lang-vi|L\u00ea V\u0103n Hi\u1ebfu}}; born 1 January 1954) is the 35th and current [[Governor of South Australia]], in office since 1 September 2014. He served as the state's [[Lieutenant-Governor (Australia)|lieutenant-governor]] from 2007 to 2014. He also served as chair of the South Australian Multicultural and Ethnic Affairs Commission (SAMEAC) from 2006 to 2009. Le is the first person [[Asian Australian|of Asian heritage]] to be appointed a state governor in Australia.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/state-politics/sa-governor-hieu-van-le-a-beacon-of-hope/story-e6frgczx-1227044320635?nk=a992bb8f1bd9a4eac9e7ae1c3765fd17| title=SA Governor Hieu Van Le 'a beacon of hope'| last=Martin| first=Sarah| newspaper=The Australian| date=2 September 2014| accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLe was born in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb]], [[South Vietnam]], on 1 January 1954. He was raised and educated in [[\u0110\u00e0 N\u1eb5ng]], and attended [[Dalat University]]. He fled Vietnam from the new communist regime in November 1977, and came by boat to [[Darwin, Northern Territory]], as a refugee in 1977 with his wife Lan and about 40 other people.<ref name=\"ADV26June\">{{cite news |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/south-australia-premier-jay-weatherill-names-hieu-van-le-as-next-governor/story-fni6uo1m-1226967500337?nk=5d3db46284fe3814b9f78235c2ef1550 |title=South Australia Premier Jay Weatherill names Hieu Van Le as next Governor |publisher=News Limited |work=The Advertiser |last=Holderhead |first=Sheradyn |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> Their two sons were born in Australia and are named after Australian cricketers [[Donald Bradman|Sir Donald Bradman]] and [[Kim Hughes]].<ref name=\"ABCNewsAppt\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-06-26/hieu-van-le-appointed-sa-governor/5552004 |title=Hieu Van Le to be next SA Governor: From war-torn Vietnam to vice-regal post |date=26 June 2014|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter arriving in Australia, Le attended the [[University of Adelaide]], receiving a [[Master of Business Administration]] and an Economics degree. He was a senior investigator and manager with the [[Australian Securities and Investments Commission]] from the early 1990s until his retirement in 2009.<ref name=\"PressJune2014\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.premier.sa.gov.au/images/news_releases/14_06June/governor.pdf |title=Hieu Van Le to be appointed as South Australia's next Governor |publisher=[[Government of South Australia]] |agency=Premier of South Australia |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=27 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924081200/http://www.premier.sa.gov.au/images/news_releases/14_06June/governor.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is also a member of the [[Australian Society of Certified Practising Accountants]] (CPA) and a Fellow Member of the [[Financial Services Institute of Australasia]] (Finsia).\n\n==Governor==\nLe's appointment as [[Governor of South Australia]] to replace [[Kevin Scarce]] was announced on 26 June 2014; he took office on 1 September, with Scarce's term expiring on 7 August.<ref name=\"ABCNewsAppt\" /><ref>{{cite web| date=13 February 2012| url=http://www.news.com.au/national/rear-admiral-kevin-scarce-to-stay-on-as-south-australia-governor/story-e6frfkp9-1226269990532| title=Rear Admiral Kevin Scarce to stay on as South Australia governor| publisher=news.com.au. |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> Le is a Catholic and credits his experiences as a refugee for strengthening his religious convictions.<ref name=\"TSC\">{{cite news | url=http://www.caa.wt2.com.au/sites/SouthernCross/features?more=5356 | title=Life's no accident | work=[[The Southern Cross (South Australia)|The Southern Cross]] | accessdate=18 December 2014 | author=DiGirolamo, Rebecca | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218001023/http://www.caa.wt2.com.au/sites/SouthernCross/features?more=5356 | archive-date=18 December 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In June 2019, Premier [[Steven Marshall]] announced that Le's original term as governor had been extended by two years, to 31 August 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://7news.com.au/politics/south-australian-governor-hieu-van-le-has-his-term-extended-by-two-years-c-157471|title=South Australian Governor Hieu Van Le has his term extended by two years|publisher=7 News|date=10 June 2019|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles and honours==\n{{Infobox viceroy styles\n| image = [[File:Badge of the Governor of South Australia.svg|50px]]\n| name = Hieu Van Le<br />(2018\u2013present)\n| dipstyle = His Excellency the Honourable\n| offstyle = Your Excellency\n| altstyle = Sir\n}}\n\n===Honours===\n;Orders\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2010: [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] (AO)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1141697&search_type=quick&showInd=true |title=LE, Hieu Van |publisher=[[Government of Australia]] |website=It's An Honour |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2014: [[Knight of Grace of the Order of St John]]\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2016: [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC)<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-06-13/sa-governor-hieu-van-le-recognised-with-a-qc/7502538 Queen's Birthday honours: SA Governor Hieu Van Le recognised with Companion Order] ''ABC News'', 13 June 2016. Retrieved 13 June 2016.</ref>\n\n;Medals\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2001: [[Centenary Medal]] \"for service to the advancement of multiculturalism in Australia\",<ref name=\"PressJune2014\"/>\n\n;Appointments\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} 2014: Colonel of the [[Royal South Australia Regiment]].\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} 2014: [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Deputy Prior of the Order of St John]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding the Most Venerable Order of St John|url=https://www.stjohnsa.com.au/cms_resources/Understanding%20the%20Most%20Venerable%20Order%20of%20St%20John.pdf|website=Governor of New South Wales|publisher=Governor of New South Wales|accessdate=24 August 2018|date=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Le Van Hieu}}\n* [http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/node/27 His Excellency the Honourable Hieu Van Le AO] at Government House SA\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080721004219/http://multicultural.sa.gov.au/commission/hieu_van_le.htm Bio Hieu Van Le] at the South Australian Multicultural and Ethnic Affairs Commission (SAMEAC)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080730034747/http://www.ministers.sa.gov.au/news.php?id=2090 From refugee to Lieutenant Governor]\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/sa/content/2006/s1935506.htm ''Stateline'' Interview] at [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bruno Krumins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lieutenant-Governor of South Australia]]|years=2007\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brenda Wilson]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kevin Scarce]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of South Australia]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian governors}}\n{{Governors of South Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Le, Hieu Van}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian accountants]]\n[[Category:Australian economists]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant-Governors of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Governors of South Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Centenary Medal]]\n[[Category:University of Adelaide alumni]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese refugees]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n\n\n{{australia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "N Panama 84534", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hieu_Van_Le"}
